The City of Johannesburg says there's no permanent solution to the raw sewage that's spilling onto properties in Houghton. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The City of Johannesburg says there's no permanent solution to the raw sewage that's spilling onto properties in Houghton. Residents on one street say they've been struggling for four years to have the issue addressed but to no avail. Each household pays about R550 per month for a sewage levy, but that seems pointless. READ: Raw sewage spills on the streets of Vaal The City of Johannesburg insists it's doing its best but it appears the City is at a loss about how to deal with the problem once and for all. "There's not a permanent plan per say to say we are going to do XYZ,” said Joburg MMC for Environment and Infrastructure Services, Nico De Jager. “We cannot put in a new line, there's so much that needs to be done in the city, that that's not on the cards."